       [ --(nnoo)ssttrriicctt ] _f_i_l_e_._t_e_x [ _f_i_l_e_2_._t_e_x ... ]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       _L_a_T_e_X_2_H_T_M_L is a Perl program that translates LaTeX source files into
       HTML. For each source file given as an argument the translator will
       create a directory containing the corresponding HTML files.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       Many options can be specified in a true/false manner. This is indicated
       by _(_n_o_), e.g. to enable passing unknown environments to LaTeX, say
       "-latex", to disable the feature say "-nolatex" or "-no_latex"
       (portability mode).

       --hheellpp | --hh
           Print this online manual and exit.

       --vveerrssiioonn | --VV
           Print the LaTeX2HTML release and version information and exit.

       --sspplliitt _n_u_m
           Stop making separate files at this depth (say "-split 0" for one
           huge HTML file).

       --lliinnkk _n_u_m
           Stop showing child nodes at this depth.

       --ttoocc__ddeepptthh _n_u_m
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)ttoocc__ssttaarrss
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)sshhoorrtt__eexxttnn
           If this is set all HTML file will have extension ".htm" instead of
           ".html". This is helpful when shipping the document to PC systems.

       --iissoo__llaanngguuaaggee _l_a_n_g
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)vvaalliiddaattee
           When this is set true, the HTML validator specified in _l_2_h_c_o_n_f_._p_m
           will run.

       --(nnoo)llaatteexx
           Pass unknown environments to LaTeX. This is the default.

       --(nnoo)ddjjggpppp
           Specify this switch if you are running DJGPP on DOS and need to
           avoid running out of filehandles.

       --(nnoo)ffoorrkk
           Enable/disable forking. The default is reasonable for this
           platform.

       --(nnoo)eexxtteerrnnaall__iimmaaggeess
           If set, leave the images outside the document.

       --(nnoo)aasscciiii__mmooddee
           This is different from --nnooiimmaaggeess.  If this is set, LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL will
           show textual tags rather than images, both in navigation panel and
           text (Eg. "[Up]" instead the up icon).  You could use this feature
           to create simple text from your document, eg. with 'Save as...
           Text' from NNeettssccaappee or with llyynnxx --dduummpp.

       --(nnoo)llccaassee__ttaaggss
           writes out HTML tag names using lowercase letters, rather than
           uppercase.

       --(nnoo)ppss__iimmaaggeess
           If set, use links to external postscript images rather than inlined
           bitmaps.

       --ffoonntt__ssiizzee _s_i_z_e
           To set the point size of LaTeX-generated GIF files, specify the
           desired value (i.e., "10pt", "11pt", "12pt", etc.).  The default is
           to use the point size of the original LaTeX document.  This value
           will be magnified by _$_F_I_G_U_R_E___S_C_A_L_E___F_A_C_T_O_R and _$_M_A_T_H___S_C_A_L_E___F_A_C_T_O_R
           defined in _l_2_h_c_o_n_f_._p_m.

       --(nnoo)tteexx__ddeeffss
           Enable interpretation of raw TeX commands (default).  Note: There
           are many variations of "\def" that LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL cannot process
           correctly!

       --(nnoo)nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put a navigation panel at the top of each page (default).

       --(nnoo)ttoopp__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Enables navigation links at the top of each page (default).

       --(nnoo)bboottttoomm__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Enables navigation links at the bottom of each page.

       --(nnoo)aauuttoo__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put navigation links at the top of each page. If the page exceeds
           _$_W_O_R_D_S___I_N___P_A_G_E number of words then put one at the bottom of the
           page.

       --(nnoo)iinnddeexx__iinn__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put a link to the index page in the navigation panel.

       --(nnoo)ccoonntteennttss__iinn__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put a link to the table of contents in the navigation panel.

       --(nnoo)nneexxtt__ppaaggee__iinn__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put a link to the next logical page in the navigation panel.

       --(nnoo)pprreevviioouuss__ppaaggee__iinn__nnaavviiggaattiioonn
           Put a link to the previous logical page in the navigation panel.

       --(nnoo)ffoooottnnooddee
           Puts all footnotes onto a separate HTML page, called _f_o_o_t_n_o_d_e_._h_t_m_l,
           rather than at the bottom of the page where they are referenced.

       --(nnoo)nnuummbbeerreedd__ffoooottnnootteess
           If true, you will get every footnote applied with a subsequent
           number, else with a generic hyperlink icon.

       --pprreeffiixx _o_u_t_p_u_t___f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e___p_r_e_f_i_x
           Set the output file prefix, prepended to all ".html", ".gif" and
           ".pl" files. See also --aauuttoo__pprreeffiixx.

       --(nnoo)aauuttoo__pprreeffiixx
           Set this to automatically insert the equivalent of --pprreeffiixx
           "basename-"", where "basename" is the base name of the file being
           translated.

       --lloonngg__ttiittlleess _n_u_m
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)ccuussttoomm__ttiittlleess
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --ttiittllee|--tt _t_o_p___p_a_g_e___t_i_t_l_e
           The title (displayed in the browser's title bar) the document shall
           get.

       --(nnoo)rrooootteedd
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --rroooottddiirr _o_u_t_p_u_t___d_i_r_e_c_t_o_r_y
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --ddiirr _o_u_t_p_u_t___d_i_r_e_c_t_o_r_y
           Put the result in this directory instead of parallel to the LaTeX
           file, provided the directory exists, or --mmkkddiirr is specified.

       --mmkkddiirr
           Allow directory specified with --ddiirr to be created if necessary.

       --aaddddrreessss _a_u_t_h_o_r___a_d_d_r_e_s_s | --nnooaaddddrreessss
           Supply a string to appear in the footer inside an <address> tag.
           --nnooaaddddrreessss suppresses the generation of an address footer.

       --(nnoo)ssuubbddiirr
           If set (default), LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL creates (or reuses) another file
           directory.  When false, the generated HTML files will be placed in
           the current directory.

       --iinnffoo _0 | _1 | _s_t_r_i_n_g
       --nnooiinnffoo
           If 0 is specified (or --nnooiinnffoo is used), do not generate an _"_A_b_o_u_t
           _t_h_i_s _d_o_c_u_m_e_n_t_._._._" section. If 1 is specified (default), the
           standard info page is generated. If a custom string is given, it is
           used as the info page.

       --(nnoo)aauuttoo__lliinnkk
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --rreeuussee _n_u_m | --nnoorreeuussee
           If false, do not reuse or recycle identical images generated in
           previous runs. If the html subdirectory already exists, start the
           interactive session.  If _n_u_m is nonzero, do recycle them and switch
           off the interactive session.  If 1, only recycle images generated
           from previous runs.  If 2, recycle images from the current and
           previous runs (default).

       --(nnoo)aannttiiaalliiaass__tteexxtt
           Use anti-aliasing in the generation of images of typeset material;
           e.g. mathematics and text, e.g. in tables and {makeimage}
           environments.

       --(nnoo)aannttiiaalliiaass
           Use anti-aliasing in the generation of images of figures. This
           usually results in "sharper" bitmap images.

       --(nnoo)ttrraannssppaarreenntt
           If this is set to false then any inlined images generated from
           "figure" environments will NOT be transparent.

       --(nnoo)wwhhiittee
           This sets the background of generated images to white for anti-
           aliasing.

       --(nnoo)ddiissccaarrdd
           if true, the PostScript file created for each generated image is
           discarded immediately after its image has been rendered and saved
           in the required graphics format. This can lead to significant
           savings in disk-space, when there are a lot of images, since
           otherwise these files are not discarded until the end of all
           processing.

       --iimmaaggee__ttyyppee _t_y_p_e
           Specify the type of bitmap images to be generated. Depending on
           your setup, LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL can generate ggiiff or ppnngg images. Note: Gif
           images have certain legal restrictions, as their generation
           involves an algorithm patented by Unisys.

       --(nnoo)iimmaaggeess
           If false, LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL will not attempt to produce any inlined
           images.  The missing images can be generated "off-line" by
           restarting LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL with --iimmaaggeess__oonnllyy.

       --aacccceenntt__iimmaaggeess _t_y_p_e | --nnooaacccceenntt__iimmaaggeess
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --ssttyyllee _s_t_y_l_e
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)ppaarrbbooxx__iimmaaggeess
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)mmaatthh
           By default the special MATH extensions are not used since they do
           not conform with the HTML 3.2 standard.

       --(nnoo)mmaatthh__ppaarrssiinngg
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)llaattiinn
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)eennttiittiieess
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)llooccaall__iiccoonnss
           Set this if you want to copy the navigation icons to each document
           directory so that the document directory is self-contained and can
           be dropped into another server tree without further actions.

       --(nnoo)ssccaallaabbllee__ffoonnttss
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)iimmaaggeess__oonnllyy
           When true, LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL will only try to convert the inlined images
           in the file _i_m_a_g_e_s_._t_e_x which should have been generated
           automatically during previous runs. This is very useful for
           correcting "bad LaTeX" in this file.

       --(nnoo)sshhooww__sseeccttiioonn__nnuummbbeerrss
           When this is set true, the section numbers are shown. The section
           numbers should then match those that would have been produced by
           LaTeX.  The correct section numbers are obtained from the $FILE.aux
           file generated by LaTeX.  Hiding the section numbers encourages use
           of particular sections as standalone documents. In this case the
           cross reference to a section is shown using the default symbol
           rather than the section number.

       --(nnoo)sshhooww__iinniitt
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --iinniitt__ffiillee _P_e_r_l___f_i_l_e
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --uupp__uurrll _u_p___U_R_L, --uupp__ttiittllee _u_p___t_i_t_l_e
       --ddoowwnn__uurrll _d_o_w_n___U_R_L, --ddoowwnn__ttiittllee _d_o_w_n___t_i_t_l_e
       --pprreevv__uurrll _p_r_e_v___U_R_L, --pprreevv__ttiittllee _p_r_e_v___t_i_t_l_e
       --iinnddeexx _i_n_d_e_x___U_R_L,
       --ccoonntteennttss _t_o_c___U_R_L
       --bbiibblliioo _b_i_b_l_i_o___U_R_L
           If both of the listed two options are set then the "Up" ("Previous"
           etc.)  button of the navigation panel in the first node/page of a
           converted document will point to _u_p___U_R_L etc. _u_p___t_i_t_l_e should be set
           to some text which describes this external link.  Similarly you
           might use these options to link external documents to your
           navigation panel.

       --eexxtteerrnnaall__ffiillee _e_x_t_e_r_n_a_l___a_u_x___f_i_l_e
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --(nnoo)sshhoorrtt__iinnddeexx
           If this is set then mmaakkeeiiddxx..ppeerrll will construct codified names for
           the text of index references.

       --(nnoo)uunnsseeggmmeenntt
           Use this to translate a segmented document as if it were not
           segmented.

       --(nnoo)ddeebbuugg
           If this is set then intermediate files are left for later
           inspection and a lot of diagnostic output is produced. This output
           may be useful when searching for problems and/or submitting bug
           reports to the developers.  Temporary files include _$_$___i_m_a_g_e_s_._t_e_x
           and _$_$___i_m_a_g_e_s_._l_o_g created during image conversion. Caution:
           Intermediate files can be _e_n_o_r_m_o_u_s!

       --ttmmpp _p_a_t_h
           Path for temporary files. This should be a local, fast filesystem
           because it is heavily used during image generation. The default is
           set in _l_2_h_c_o_n_f_._p_m.

       --(nnoo)lldduummpp
           This will cause LaTeX2HTML to produce a LaTeX dump of images.tex
           which is read in on subsequent runs and speeds up startup time of
           LaTeX on the images.tex translation. This actually consumes
           additional time on the first run, but pays off on subsequent runs.
           The dump file will need about 1 Meg of disk space.

       --(nnoo)ttiimmiinngg
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

       --vveerrbboossiittyy _n_u_m
           The amount of message information printed to the screen during
           processing by LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL is controlled by this setting.  By
           increasing this value, more information is displayed.  Here is the
           type of extra information that is shown at each level:

             0   no extra information
             1   section types and titles
             2   environment
             3   command names
             4   links, labels and internal sectioning codes

       --hhttmmll__vveerrssiioonn _l_i_s_t
           Which HTML version should be generated. Currently available are:
           2.0, 3.0, 3.2, 4.0. Some additional options that may be added are:
           "math" (parse mathematics), "i18n" (?), "table" (generate tables),
           "frame" (generate frames), "latin1"..."latin9" (use ISO-Latin-x
           encoding), "unicode" (generate unicode characters). Separate the
           options with ',', e.g. "4.0,math,frame".

       --(nnoo)ssttrriicctt
           MISSING_DESCRIPTION

FFIILLEESS
       _$_L_A_T_E_X_2_H_T_M_L_P_L_A_T_D_I_R_/_l_2_h_c_o_n_f_._p_m
           This file holds the global defaults and configuration settings for
           LLaaTTeeXX22HHTTMMLL.

       _$_H_O_M_E_/_._l_a_t_e_x_2_h_t_m_l_-_i_n_i_t
       _._/_._l_a_t_e_x_2_h_t_m_l_-_i_n_i_t
           These files may contain settings that override the global defaults,
           just like specifying command line switches.

EENNVVIIRROONNMMEENNTT
       LATEX2HTMLDIR
           Path where LaTeX2HTML library files are found. On this installation
           LATEX2HTMLDIR is _/_u_s_r_/_l_o_c_a_l_/_C_e_l_l_a_r_/_l_a_t_e_x_2_h_t_m_l_/_2_0_1_7_._2

       PERL5LIB
           Set by the llaatteexx22hhttmmll program to find perl modules.

       L2HCONFIG
           An alternative configuration filename. The standard configuration
           file is _$_L_A_T_E_X_2_H_T_M_L_P_L_A_T_D_I_R_/_l_2_h_c_o_n_f_._p_m. You may specify a sole
           filename (searched for in _$_L_A_T_E_X_2_H_T_M_L_P_L_A_T_D_I_R (and _$_P_E_R_L_5_L_I_B) or a
           complete path.

       L2HINIT_NAME
           The standard user-specific configuration filename is
           _._l_a_t_e_x_2_h_t_m_l_-_i_n_i_t.  This environment variable will override this
           name.

       HOME
           Evaluated if the system does not know about "home" directories
           (like DOS, WinXX, OS/2, ...) to determine the path to
           _$_L_2_H_I_N_I_T___N_A_M_E.

       TEXE_DONT_INCLUDE, TEXE_DO_INCLUDE
           Used internally for communication with tteexxeexxppaanndd.

       TEXINPUTS
           Used to find TeX includes of all sorts.

PPRROOBBLLEEMMSS
       For information on various problems and remedies see the WWW online
       documentation or the documents available in the distribution.  An
       online bug reporting form and various archives are available at
       _h_t_t_p_:_/_/_w_w_w_._l_a_t_e_x_2_h_t_m_l_._o_r_g_/

